70\u201380%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Barack Obama]]\n| before_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| after_party = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n[[File:United States presidential election in Washington, 2016, results by county.png|thumb|right|400px|Results by county showing number of votes by size and candidates by color]]\n[[File:United States presidential election in Washington, 2016.svg|thumb|390px|Treemap of the popular vote by county]]\n{{ElectionsWA}}\n\nThe '''2016 United States presidential election in Washington''' was won by Hillary Rodham Clinton on November 8, 2016, with 54.3% of the vote over [[Hillary Clinton|Donald Trump]]'s 38.07%. All of [[Washington (state)|Washington's]] 12 [[United States Electoral College|electoral votes]] were assigned to Clinton, though four [[faithless elector|defected]]. Trump prevailed in the [[2016 United States presidential election|presidential election]] nationally.\n\nIn the [[United States presidential primary|presidential primaries]], Washington voters chose [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Party's nominee; the [[Washington State Democratic Party|Democratic]] Party used the caucus system, and [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] nominee was chosen in a convention.\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|Political party strength in Washington (state)}}\nWashington has voted for the Democratic candidate in every presidential election since [[1988 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|1988]]. While the state's Senate was majority Republican in 2016, both of Washington's United States Senators are Democrats, as well as a majority of the state's U.S. House delegation. Barack Obama defeated [[John McCain]] by 17.08% in [[2008 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|2008]] and [[Mitt Romney]] by 14.93% in [[2012 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|2012]].\n\n== Primary elections ==\n\n=== Democratic caucus ===\n{{main|2016 Washington Democratic caucuses}}\n[[File:Washington Democratic Presidential Caucuses Election Results by County, 2016.svg|thumb|County results of the Washington Democratic presidential caucus, 2016.\n{{legend|#228b22|Bernie Sanders}}]] Bernie Sanders bested Hillary Clinton in the Democratic presidential caucus on March 26, 2016:\n\nThe state also held a non-binding presidential primary on May 24, the same date as the state's Republican primary. Hillary Clinton won the preference vote.\n\n{{2016WADem}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Washington Democratic primary, May 24, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | Popular vote\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! Count\n! Percentage\n! <small>Pledged</small>\n! <small>Unpledged</small>\n! <small>Total</small>\n|- {{party shading/Democratic}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 420,461\n| 52.38%\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n| 382,293\n| 47.62%\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Others\n| \n| \n| || ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n! Total\n! 802,754\n! 100%\n! 0\n! 0\n! 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''[http://results.vote.wa.gov/results/20160524/Federal-All.html Washington Secretary of State - Official Results]''\n|}\n\n=== Republican primary ===\n{{main|2016 Washington Republican primary}}\nFour candidates appeared on the Republican presidential primary ballot on May 24, 2016:\n\n*[[Ben Carson]] (withdrawn)\n*[[Ted Cruz]] (withdrawn)\n*[[John Kasich]] (withdrawn)\n*[[Donald Trump]]\n\n{{2016WARep}}\n\n===Green convention===\nThis state's Green Party state convention was on May 15. Ballots were emailed to members within a week after the convention.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/events/965157636872423/</ref>\n\n{| class=\"infobox bordered\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"margin:1em 1em 1em 0; font-size:95%; text-align:right; float:none; clear:none;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" | Washing Green Party Convention, May 15, 2016.\n|-  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"| Candidate\n! style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"| Votes\n! style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"| Percentage\n! style=\"vertical-align:middle;\"| National delegates\n|- style=\"background:lightgreen;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''Jill Stein'''\n| '''-'''\n| '''91.7'''\n| '''5'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|William Kreml\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Sedinam Kinamo Christin Moyowasifza Curry\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Kent Mesplay\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Darryl Cherney\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"margin-right:0.50px\"| '''Total'''\n| style=\"margin-right:0.50px\"|'''-'''\n| style=\"margin-right:0.50px\"|'''-'''\n| style=\"margin-right:0.50px\"|'''5'''\n|}\n\n==General election==\n{{more citations needed|section|reason=Sources needed for results|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Polling===\n{{see also|Statewide opinion polling for the United States presidential election, 2016#Washington}}\n\n===State voting history===\nWashington joined the Union in November 1889 and has participated in all elections from 1892 onwards.\n\nSince 1900, Washington voted Democratic 51.72 percent of the time and Republican 44.83 percent of the time. Since 1988, Washington had voted for the Democratic Party in each presidential election, and the same was expected to happen in 2016.<ref>[http://usaelections-2016.com/washington-presidential-election-2016-results-live-updates/957/ Washington Presidential Election 2016 Results LIVE Updates]</ref>\n\n===Results===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | United States presidential election in Washington, 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=November 8, 2016 General Election Results (Washington)|url=http://results.vote.wa.gov/results/20161108/Federal-All.html|publisher=Washington Secretary of State|accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Running mate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]'''\n| '''[[Hillary Clinton]]'''\n| '''[[Tim Kaine]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,742,718'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''54.30%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''8'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[Donald Trump]]\n| [[Mike Pence]]\n| align=\"right\" | 1,221,747\n| align=\"right\" | 38.07%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Gary Johnson]] \n| [[William Weld]]\n| align=\"right\" | 160,879\n| align=\"right\" | 5.01%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background:grey; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Write-in candidate|Write-ins]]\n|\n|\n| align=\"right\" | 102,416\n| align=\"right\" | 3.23%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#0BDA51; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n| [[Jill Stein]]\n| [[Ajamu Baraka]]\n| align=\"right\" | 58,417\n| align=\"right\" | 1.82%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#D2B48C; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution]]\n| [[Darrell Castle]]\n| [[Scott Bradley (politician)|Scott Bradley]]\n| align=\"right\" | 17,623\n| align=\"right\" | 0.55%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#CC0000; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|Socialist Workers]] \n| [[Alyson Kennedy]]\n| [[Osborne Hart]]\n| align=\"right\" | 4,307\n| align=\"right\" | 0.13%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:black; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Party for Socialism and Liberation|Socialism and Liberation]]\n| [[Gloria La Riva]]\n| [[Eugene Puryear]]\n| align=\"right\" | 3,523\n| align=\"right\" | 0.11%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[Colin Powell]]\n| \n| align=\"right\" | 0\n| align=\"right\" | 0.00%\n| align=\"right\" | 3\n|-\n! style=\"background:grey; width:3px;\"|\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n| [[Faith Spotted Eagle]] \n| [[Winona LaDuke]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.00%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1\n|-\n\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals (excluding write-ins)'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''3,209,214\t'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.00%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''12'''\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n\n|}\n\n====Analysis====\nHillary Clinton won the election in Washington with 54.3 percent of the vote, a slightly reduced percentage from [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] in [[2012 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|2012]]. However, Washington was among the states in which Hillary Clinton outperformed Barack Obama's winning margin in 2012, despite the Democratic nominee losing the Electoral College this time. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/2016/results/washington|title=Washington Election Results 2016|date=2017-08-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Donald Trump received 38.1 percent of the vote. This was the first presidential election in which the Republican Party won [[Grays Harbor County, Washington|Grays Harbor]] and [[Pacific County, Washington|Pacific Counties]] since [[1928 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|1928]] and [[1952 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|1952]] respectively.<ref>http://results.vote.wa.gov/results/20161108/pacific/</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wheel|first1=Robert|title=The 2016 Streak Breakers|url=http://www.centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/articles/the-2016-streak-breakers/|website=Center for Politics|publisher=Larry J. Sabato\u2019s Crystal Ball|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> It was also the first time the GOP had won Cowlitz County since Ronald Reagan in 1980, and the first Republican win in [[Mason County, Washington|Mason County]] since Reagan in 1984.<ref name=\"how\">Sullivan, Robert David; [http://www.americamagazine.org/content/unconventional-wisdom/how-red-and-blue-map-evolved-over-past-century \u2018How the Red and Blue Map Evolved Over the Past Century\u2019]; ''America Magazine'' in ''The National Catholic Review''; June 29, 2016</ref>\n\nDespite Clinton's victory, four Democratic electors [[faithless elector|defected]]. Three voted for [[Colin Powell]], making him the first African-American Republican to receive electoral votes, while a Native American activist cast his vote for [[Faith Spotted Eagle]], making her the first Native American to receive an electoral vote for president.\n\nPowell became the first Republican to receive electoral votes from Washington state since [[Ronald Reagan]] in [[1984 United States presidential election in Washington (state)|1984]].<ref name=\"how\"/> However, overall it was the eighth consecutive election in which Washington voted Democratic, and the twelfth in a row in which it voted the same way as neighboring [[2016 United States presidential election in Oregon|Oregon]].\n\n===By county===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! County\n! Clinton%\n! Clinton#\n! Trump%\n! Trump#\n! Others (excluding write-ins)%\n! Others (excluding write-ins)#\n! Total\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Adams County, Washington|Adams County]] || 28.32% || 1,299|| '''67.21%''' || '''3,083''' || 5.64% || 262 || '''4,644''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Asotin County, Washington|Asotin County]] || 32.59% || 3,134|| '''59.70%''' || '''5,741''' || 8.84% || 861 || '''9,736''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Benton County, Washington|Benton County]] || 33.26% || 26,360|| '''59.55%''' || '''47,194''' || 8.09%|| 6,473 || '''80,027''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Chelan County, Washington|Chelan County]] || 39.34% || 13,032|| '''54.68%''' || '''18,114''' || 6.69% || 2,234 || '''33,380''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Clallam County, Washington|Clallam County]] || 45.19% || 17,677|| '''48.04%''' || '''18,794''' || 7.57% || 2,986 || '''39,457''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Clark County, Washington|Clark County]] || '''46.70%''' || '''92,757'''|| 46.54% || 92,441 ||  7.48% || 14,962 || '''200,160''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Columbia County, Washington|Columbia County]] || 24.37% || 526|| '''69.37%''' || '''1,497''' || 7.29% || 159 || '''2,182''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]] || 39.60% || 17,908|| '''53.48%''' || '''24,185''' || 7.88% || 3,599 || '''45,692''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Douglas County, Washington|Douglas County]] || 31.89% || 4,918|| '''62.28%''' || '''9,603''' || 6.58% || 1,022 || '''15,543''' \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Ferry County, Washington|Ferry County]] || 30.94% || 1,098|| '''62.05%''' || '''2,202''' || 8.36% || 301 || '''3,601''' \n|-\n|{{Party s